MINI-PROJECT 3: EFFECTIVE BAG CAPACITY (PHYSICAL & OPERATIONAL MODEL)

Real-World problem:

Most systems treat bag capacity as purely theoretical number (volume or item count). In real operations, this leads to recurring issues:
- Cardboard bags break when weight is too high.
- Cold orders require ice, which has a real physical cost (weight and space).
- Some products (e. g., bottles, eggs, glass, yogurt, tomatoes) must be kept upright or protected, wasting effective space.
- Oversized or heavy items (e. g., ham legs, mop sticks, charcoal) do not fit any standard bag and should not be treated as "normal packing".
- As a result, systems either overpack, trigger rework downstream or rely on manual judgment outside the system.

The core problem is that the model uses theoretical capacity instead of effective, operational capacity.

What this model change introduces:

This mini-project replaces "theoretical capacity" with an effective, conservative and operational capacity policy that reflects physical and safety constraints:
- Different flows are modeled explicitly via BagType:
  - LIGHT_AMBIENT: cardboard bag, strict closing constraints.
  - HARD_AMBIENT: no bag at all (1 product = 1 unit, SLAM attached directly).
  - CHILLED / FROZEN: special inner ice bag + flexible outer bag.
- Capacity is validated by a policy (CapacityPolicy) instead of scattered checks.
- The policy accounts for:
  - Weight limits (human handling safety).
  - Effective volume, not just theoretical volume.
  - Fragile products, which pack worse and require artificial volume penalties.
  - Ice blocks for cold bags, whose amount depends on outside temperature.
 
The result is a model that is boring, explicit, auditable and closer to reality.

Bag types operational rules:

HARD_AMBIENT (no bag)
- Rule: only one product is allowed.
- Rationale: oversized or heavy items (e. g., ham leg, mop stick, charcoal) receive the SLAM label directly on the product.
- These items do not participate in any bag capacity calculation.

LIGHT_AMBIENT (cardboard bag):
- Max weight: 12 kg (safety limit to avoid bag breakage during handling).
- Operational volume limit for closing: 50.000 cm3.
- Even if the theoretical bag volume is higher, the system validates against the operational closing limit.
- Fragile products:
  - Their volume is counted as volume * 1.20.
  - This models orientation constraints, gaps and "cannot be compressed" behavior.

CHILLED / FROZEN (special inner bag + flexible outer bag):

- Ice blocks are placed in a special flexible inner bag, which then fits into a larger flexible outer bag.
- Because of this:
  - There is no volume constraint related to folding/closing the bag.
  - There is a weight constraint: 15 kg (standard handling safety limit).
- Ice has a real physical cost:
  - Each block weighs 0.4 kg and occupies approximately 500 cm3.
  - Ice adds both weight and volume to the bag contents.

Ice amount depends on outside temperature:
- Temperature range: 10ºC --> 40ºC.
- Linear interpolation within this range:
  - CHILLED: 3-7 blocks.
  - FROZEN: 7-12 blocks.
   
The system clamps the temperature to this range and computes the required number of blocks accordingly. This makes cold packing context-aware and predictable.

Fragile product (all areas):
- The model uses a single flag: fragile.
- If a product si fragile its volume is counted with a +20% artificial penalty.
- This serves two purposes:
  - For models worse packing efficiency (upright, protected, spaced).
  - Allows downstream systems (e. g. SLAM/labels) to mark the bag as FRAGILE.
- This applies to: LIGHT_AMBIENT, CHILLED, FROZEN; in HARD_AMBIENT there is no bag, but the flag is still relevant as a warning.

Trade-offs:

Costs:
- Lower packing density in some scenarios.
- More bags or trips in edge cases.
- The model is conservative by design.

Benefits:
- Better physical safety (weight handling, bag integrity).
- Fewer broken or unstable bags.
- Less downstream rework.
- More predictable and explainable behavior.
- Capacity becomes an explicit policy instead of an implicit assumption.

Out of Scope:

This mini-project does not address:
- Geometric packing optimization.
- Picking area routing.
- Batch/orchestration logic.
- UI or operator workflows.

Its only goal is to replace theoretical capacity with effective, operational capacity.

Where this lives in the code:

This behavior is modeled mainly in:
- BagType.
- Product.
- CapacityPolicy.
- EffectiveCapacityPolicy.
